Remarks: This species is previously known from Australia and South Africa . The measurements and shape of structures fit generally well the previous descriptions of
N . benjamini
(
Schicha 1981
, 1987 ;
Ueckermann & Loots 1988
;
Beard 2001
). However, as indicated above, the Brazilian population examined in this study has a variable number of teeth on both cheliceral digits (
Fig. 7
). This was confirmed from the examination of eight specimens collected from a same host (
B . decumbens
) in a same collecting site (São José do Rio Preto), seven of them collected on a same date. In some specimens, the variability was observed even between right and the left chelicerae.
